                    <h1><a name="7"></a>7. Pain perception</h1>
                    <p><a href="#home">Home</a></p>
                    <p><strong>Basics of pain: </strong>There are two types of pain: the first type is fast and acute (e.g., sticking a needle in your skin), the second type is prolonged and throbbing (e.g., muscle pain). And those two types exist for a reason &mdash; the fast pain is about getting you to move as quickly as possible(from the source of the piercing pain) while the slow pain is about making sure you don&rsquo;t move too much, so you can heal. Those two types of pain are results of different neural stimulation patterns. The fast pain stimulates neuron X first (which causes pain) and immediately neuron Y (which inhibits pain). The positive signal from X causes pain and the negative signal from Y right afterward offsets the pain. The slow pain, instead, stimulates neuron X and inhibits neutron Y &mdash; resulting in prolonged pain sensation.</p>
                    <p><strong>How does stress impact paint perception? </strong>Contrary to the topics we have covered so far, for one time, stress does not seem to have a strong negative impact on pain perception. In some cases, stress blocks pain perception. How? through the release of opioid peptides (for example, endorphins) that binds with opioid receptors in the brain and provides pain relief (this explains runner&rsquo;s high). All sorts of other stressors produce similar effects, surgery, low blood sugar, exposure to cold, childbirth etc. Opiates (analgesics not produced by the body) has a similar chemical structure to those of opioids (analgesics produced by the body like endorphins) and hence bind to receptors in the brain to get to the same level of pain reduction.</p>
                    <h1><a name="8"></a>8. Learning and memory</h1>
                    <p><a href="#home">Home</a></p>
                    <p><strong>Basics of memory</strong></p>
                    <p>Memory storage and memory formation/retrieval have very different pathways in our brain. A cheesy analogy of this pair is the hard drive (memory storage) and keyboard (memory formation/retrieval). Cortex is the hard-drive and hippocampus is the keyboard, by which you place and access memories in the context. Note that hippocampus is also the center of emotion, which partially explains why your level of memory towards certain events is impacted by the strengths of emotions. However, the key word here is &ldquo;partially&rdquo; because this statement is not entirely true. &mdash; the hippocampus is only involved in the formation of explicit memory (like facts, knowledge, and events), but not implicit memory (procedural things like how to walk, hit tennis balls, etc.). People who have their hippocampus destroyed cannot form new explicit memories, much like what we see in the movie &ldquo;Momento&rdquo; (really great movie by the way if you haven&rsquo;t seen it). But they can still learn skills like playing the piano.</p>
                    <p>Hippocampus and cortex form memories through synapses. And they disproportionately make use of what is probably the most excitatory neurotransmitter there is &mdash; glutamate. Glutamatergic synapses have an interesting property &mdash; it has an all-or-nothing type of personality. It will only pass on (massive) excitement when a certain threshold is passed. This explains why it takes repetition to learn something (you need to reach that threshold), it is the underlying biological mechanism of &ldquo;aha&rdquo; moments during learning. And what&rsquo;s even cooler is, sometimes when a synapse had a sufficient number of super excitatory glutamate-driven &ldquo;aha&rsquo;s&rdquo;, the synapse becomes persistently more excitable. So next time it takes less to get the &ldquo;aha&rdquo;. Our learning ability can be strengthened &mdash; and such strengthening can be long term. There&rsquo;s also increasing evidence that the formation of new memories might also come from the formation of new connections between neutrons and, even formation of new neutrons themselves. Here, you have a molecular level mechanism of the famous &ldquo;growth mindset&rdquo;</p>
                    <p>In conclusion, you can gain memories in four ways. The first two are well-documented and the last two are emerging hypotheses with some evidence.</p>
                    <ol>
                      <li>Exciting current neuron pathways &mdash; get the &ldquo;aha&rdquo; moment</li>
                      <li>Strengthening the potential of pre-existing neutrons through repeated exposure &mdash; make it easier to get the &ldquo;aha&rdquo; moment next time</li>
                      <li>Formation of new connections between neurons</li>
                      <li>Or even, the formation of new neurons themselves</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p><strong>How does stress impact memory?</strong></p>
                    <p>So how does stress come in here? It turns out that short-term stress can enhance memory. It makes sense because both memory retrieval and memory formation can help you get out of stressful situations and also have better odds of surviving the next similar stressor. However, as usual, long-term stress is really bad news for memories, particularly hippocampus-dependent explicit memories. And it does so in many ways: it disrupts long-term potentiation of neural pathways; it disconnects pre-existing neural networks, and it inhibits the birth of new neurons &mdash; pretty much it impacts everything that we mentioned above about memory formation. The important thing here to note is &mdash; During stress, the neural pathways in hippocampus begin to shrivel, to atrophy and retract a bit (you can actually observe the shrinkage visually when looking at lab animals under long-term stress). But that doesn&rsquo;t mean memory is lost, it means it&rsquo;s harder to retrieve (you need more complex and different pathway to retrieve a fact), and that&rsquo;s different from permanent loss in say, late-stage Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease or a massive stroke, where vast acres of neurons in the hippocampus is lost.</p>
                    <h1><a name="9"></a>9. Sleep</h1>
                    <p><a href="#home">Home</a></p>
                    <p>I just finished reading the book &ldquo;Why we sleep&rdquo; by Matthew Walker (which I highly recommend) and can write more details about stress and its impact on sleep later. But just to add a few notes here:</p>
                    <ul>
                      <li>About 75% of cases of insomnia are triggered by some major stressor.</li>
                      <li>Stress not only disrupts the the total amount of sleep but can decrease the quality of sleep. It disproportionally reduces your deep sleep (slow wave sleep) &mdash; which is what you need for energy restoration.</li>
                      <li>And this is a vicious cycle. Stress disrupts sleep, poor sleep activates more stress-response, which leads to even worse sleep, it goes on.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h1><a name="10"></a>10. Depression</h1>
                    <p><a href="#home">Home</a></p>
                    <p>We have now seen some important links between stress and depression: extremes of psychological stress can cause something in a lab animal that looks pretty close to a depression. When animals are exposed to uncontrollable stressors (e.g., random electric shock), they have trouble coping with all sorts of normal life tasks. This is both due to simply not trying to cope with stress and move on in life, and also not reacting to any improvement from the normal coping mechanism. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t control what&rsquo;s happening to me, ever. So why bother?&rdquo;. Much of what constitutes a depression is centered around responding to one awful thing and overgeneralizing from it &mdash; cognitively distorting how the world works. According to Marty Seligman&rsquo;s &ldquo;learned helplessness&rdquo; model, depression is not generalized pessimism, but pessimism specific to the efforts of one&rsquo;s own skilled action. Subjected to enough uncontrollable stress, we learn to be helpless &mdash; we lack the motivation to try to live because we assume the worst; we lack the cognitive clarity to perceive when things are actually going fine, and we feel an aching lack of pleasure in everything.</p>
                    <h1><a name="11"></a>11. Dealing with stress</h1>
                    <p><a href="#home">Home</a></p>
                    <p>By now, if you are like me, you probably feel pretty devastated at the massive negative impact of stress on your body. However, when there are trends, there are also outliers. In the relationship of stress and health and aging, it&rsquo;s the outliers that offer interesting insights. When we look at those outliers, we can find a few stress reduction mechanisms:</p>
                    <ul>
                      <li><strong>Outlets for frustration</strong> &mdash; this is frequently practiced by primates. An alpha male who just lost a fight often lets the frustration out by beating up lower rank males or rape females. Unfortunately, this coping mechanism also explains misplaced aggression in human behaviors</li>
                      <li><strong>Social support</strong> &mdash; baboons who have a bigger social circle, who are groomed more frequently have lower glucocorticoids levels. This is true for humans as well &mdash; just look at the Harvard Study of &ldquo;a good life&rdquo; <a href="https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2017/04/over-nearly-80-years-harvard-study-has-been-showing-how-to-live-a-healthy-and-happy-life/"  rel="noopener nofollow">Over nearly 80 years, Harvard study has been showing how to live a healthy and happy life &mdash; Harvard Gazette</a></li>
                      <li><strong>Predictability</strong> makes stressors less stressful (its less about the intensity of the stressor, but about anticipation. A study looked at the stress level of civilians during wartime in London. Researchers noticed that suburban population developed more ulcers (a proxy for the level of stress) compared to urban population &mdash; this is because the bombing in the suburbs is less frequent and more unpredictable in timing.</li>
                      <li><strong>Control</strong> &mdash; Studies have shown that if you give chronic pain patients the ability to control their own painkiller dosage (they can press a button to increase dosage). Miraculously, the total amount of pain killer consumed decreased. It is the sense of control that&rsquo;s doing wonders here. And it&rsquo;s not just the exercise of control, it&rsquo;s the perception of control, that matters here.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>These coping mechanisms are profound and offer hope. The good old wisdom from your grandmother is still among the best things we can do to live a long and healthy life &mdash; going for a run, punching a few sandbags, spending time with friends and family, meditating, focusing on things you can control, and having the cognitive flexibility to switch between internal and external locus of control.</p>
                    <p>To end this summary on a high-note, quoting Sapolsky directly:</p>
                    <p>&ldquo;God grant me the serenity to accept the things I cannot change, courage to change the things I can, and wisdom to know the difference. &mdash; have the wisdom to pick your battles. And once you have, the flexibility and resiliency of strategies to use in those battles are summarized in something I once heard: in the face of strong winds, let me be a blade of grass; in the face of strong walls, let me be a gale of wind.</p>
                    <p>In our privileged lives, we are uniquely smart enough to have invented stressors and uniquely foolish enough to have let them, too often, dominate our lives. Surely we have the potential to be uniquely wise enough to banish their stressful hold&rdquo;</p>
