      <h1>Introduction</h1>
      <p>This book presents research evidence on the (mostly negative) impact of stress on your body functions, from hormonal balance to cardiovascular risk, from growth to reproductive system &mdash; everything.</p>
      <p>This summary pretty closely follows the structure of the book. We will start with the molecular mechanism of stress response and then look at the relationship between stress and some of our key body functions. Lastly, we also take a brief look at stress coping mechanisms.</p>
      <p><b>The reason zebras don't get ulcers (<i>am I answering this too soon?</i>) derives from Sapolsky's idea that for animals such as zebras, stress is generally episodic (e.g., running away from a lion), while for humans, stress is often chronic (e.g., worrying about losing your job).<br>
        AGAIN:  The reason is because they (zebras) only have to deal with acute physical stressors, whereas people are stressed all the time!<br>
